{"questionId":"19582","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Using geometry software, Pedro draws a quadrilateral <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>ABCD</mtext></math>. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>AB</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>CD</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math>. Angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>BAD</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>51</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>°</mo></math> and angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>ADB</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>52</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>°</mo></math>. This information is shown in the diagram.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/8dda9f59789003d94f7e251a0c49f5d4e2888bbe.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>CE</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math>, where point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>E</mtext></math> is the midpoint of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>BD</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Show that angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>EDC</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>48</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>°</mo></math>, correct to three significant figures.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mtext>EDC</mtext><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>94582</mn><msup><mo>…</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mn>7</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>94582</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em><strong>(ft)<em>(M1)(A1)</em>(ft)</strong></p>\n<p><em><strong><br></strong></em><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em> for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>94582</mn><mo>…</mo></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>89164</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;seen, <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for substituted cosine rule, <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em><strong>(ft)</strong> for correct substitutions.</p>\n<p><br><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mtext>EDC</mtext><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>47</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9515</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>°</mo></math><strong>&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>48</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>°</mo></math>&nbsp;(<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp;sig figures)<strong>&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(AG)</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Both an unrounded answer that rounds to the given answer&nbsp;and the rounded value must be seen for the final <strong><em>(M1)</em></strong> to be awarded.<br>Award at most <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em><strong>(ft)<em>(M1)</em></strong><em><strong>(A1)</strong></em><strong>(ft)<em>(A0)</em></strong>&nbsp;if the known angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>48</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>°</mo></math> is used to validate the result. Follow through from their<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>&nbsp;BD</mtext></math> in part (a).</p>\n<p><em><strong><br></strong></em><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19582","referenceCode":"20N.2.SL.TZ0.T_3b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Show that angle EDC=48.0°, correct to three significant figures.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.2—2d and 3d trig, sine rule, cosine rule, area"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}